I explained how it felt the best in the morning after sleeping with my [triangle wedge pillow]( https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009HHLBKK/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&tag=bonktothefi07-20&camp=1789&creative=9325&linkCode=as2&creativeASIN=B009HHLBKK&linkId=51cc089424f4338abd4ac776a375f6cb) that I use to elevate my legs.
The pain gradually worsened during the day until I could return home and go back to elevating my legs for the rest of the night.
Ice was no help, or at least that's how it felt.
I could bend my knee less and less as the day went on.
Also that the pain was getting worse, not better with time.

> It was a quick diagnosis of bursitis in both knees and a burst Baker’s cyst in the back of my right knee.

After running through my symptoms I had a check up on my knees and calves.
It was a quick diagnosis of bursitis in both knees and a burst Baker’s cyst in the back of my right knee.
Basically the fluid build-up is from overuse.
However, the fluid sac (Baker’s cyst) actually bursting is what caused the pain in my upper calf.
And then I ran on that for 60 more miles.
So needless to say my right leg was not in great shape.

